var definitions = ['<h2>Pablo e Carmen são amigos.</h2><div><strong>Pablo</strong> This is a proper noun, a given name in Portuguese. It’s equivalent to "Pablo" in English and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect nouns or phrases within a sentence.</div><div><strong>Carmen</strong> This is another proper noun, a given name in Portuguese, equivalent to "Carmen" in English. It’s the second subject of the compound subject in the sentence.</div><div><strong>são</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being or relationship between Pablo and Carmen.</div><div><strong>amigos</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "friends", and it’s the complement of the sentence. It is in the masculine plural form and denotes a friendship or friendly relationship between the subjects.</div>','<h2>É acessível e de boa qualidade.</h2><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, which means "to be". It indicates a state of being or existence related to the subject, in this case referring to something that is affordable or accessible.</div><div><strong>acessível</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective that means "accessible" or "affordable". In this context, it describes something that is easy to reach, obtain, or use.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "and". It’s a conjunction used to connect words or phrases with a similar function or role within a sentence.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This Portuguese preposition generally means "of" or "from". In this context, it is used to link the adjective "boa" to the noun "qualidade", forming the phrase "of good quality".</div><div><strong>boa</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "good". It modifies the noun that follows, expressing that it has positive attributes or qualities.</div><div><strong>qualidade</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "quality". When paired with the adjective "boa", it refers to something having a high standard or level of excellence.</div>','<h2>Tem ketchup e mostarda em seu cachorro-quente.</h2><div><strong>Tem</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "ter" in Portuguese, which means "to have". In this context, it’s used to indicate that something contains or possesses what follows.</div><div><strong>ketchup</strong> A loan word from English, "ketchup" in Portuguese refers to the same tomato-based condiment widely used internationally.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "and". It’s a conjunction used to connect words or phrases, indicating that what follows is in addition to what has come before.</div><div><strong>mostarda</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "mustard", referring to the condiment often paired with ketchup.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can translate to "in", "on", or "at" in English. It’s used here to specify the location of the ketchup and mustard.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective that means "your" in English. It shows that the hot dog belongs to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>cachorro-quente</strong> This is the Portuguese term for "hot dog", which is a common fast-food item consisting of a grilled or steamed sausage served in the slit of a partially sliced bun.</div>','<h2>Tem maçãs e laranjas no cesto.</h2><div><strong>Tem</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ter" in Portuguese, which means "to have". In this context, it is used as an impersonal verb roughly translating to "there are" in English, indicating the existence of something.</div><div><strong>maçãs</strong> This is the plural of "maçã", which means "apple" in Portuguese. It is a noun, and in this sentence, it represents one of the items that are in the basket.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word is the conjunction "and" in Portuguese. It is used to connect the nouns "maçãs" and "laranjas", indicating that there is more than one type of fruit in the basket.</div><div><strong>laranjas</strong> This is the plural form of "laranja", which means "orange" in Portuguese. Like "maçãs", it is a noun, and it represents another type of fruit that is found in the basket.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), which translates to "in the" in English. It connects the verb "tem" to the noun "cesto", indicating the location where the apples and oranges are.</div><div><strong>cesto</strong> This word means "basket" in Portuguese. It is a noun and serves as the place where the apples and oranges are located, as mentioned in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Tenho um gato e um cachorro.</h2><div><strong>Tenho</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It indicates possession or ownership in this context.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a Portuguese indefinite article for masculine singular nouns, meaning "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>gato</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "cat". It is masculine and singular to correspond with the article "um".</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words or phrases of the same type.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is another occurrence of the Portuguese indefinite article for masculine singular nouns, meaning "a" or "an" in English. It precedes another masculine singular noun.</div><div><strong>cachorro</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "dog". It is masculine and singular to match with the preceding article "um".</div>','<h2>Você quer ir ao cinema ou ao restaurante?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used as the subject of the sentence to address the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>quer</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". It is conjugated to match the second-person singular subject "você".</div><div><strong>ir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to go". In Portuguese, infinitives can be used after other verbs to indicate an action that is to be completed.</div><div><strong>ao</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) with the masculine singular article "o" (the), translating as "to the" in English. It is used twice, before "cinema" and "restaurante".</div><div><strong>cinema</strong> This is a masculine singular noun that means "cinema" or "movie theater" in English.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This word translates to "or" in English. It’s a conjunction used to offer a choice or alternative between two options.</div><div><strong>ao restaurante?</strong> Here, "ao" again means "to the" and "restaurante" is a masculine singular noun that means "restaurant". The question mark indicates that this is a question, asking whether the person wants to go to the restaurant as an alternative to the cinema.</div>','<h2>O que você vai comer, a maçã ou o bolo?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is an interrogative pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "what" in English. It’s used here to introduce a question.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person subject pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. In Brazil, it’s widely used as a formal or informal address.</div><div><strong>vai</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ir" in the present tense in Brazilian Portuguese, but when used with another verb (comer in this case), it denotes a future tense, equivalent to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>comer</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to eat" in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>maçã</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in Portuguese, meaning "apple".</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the conjunction "or" in Portuguese, used to offer a choice or alternative.</div><div><strong>o</strong> Again, this is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>bolo</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, meaning "cake".</div>','<h2>Você quer o relógio preto ou o branco?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here as the subject of the sentence, addressing someone directly.</div><div><strong>quer</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". In this case, conjugated to agree with "Você" (you).</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>relógio</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "watch" or "clock". It is masculine and singular in this instance.</div><div><strong>preto</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "black". Here, it’s used as the masculine singular to agree with the noun "relógio".</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This word translates to "or" in English. It’s a conjunction used to present an alternative or choice between two items.</div><div><strong>o</strong> Again, this is the masculine singular definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English, repeated here before the alternative option.</div><div><strong>branco?</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "white". It is similar to "preto" but presents the alternate color choice for the watch. It’s also in the masculine singular form to agree with "relógio". The sentence ends with a question mark, indicating that it’s a question.</div>','<h2>Qual você prefere? O cinza ou o branco?</h2><div><strong>Qual</strong> This is a Portuguese interrogative pronoun meaning "which" or "what". It is used when asking for a selection or choice from a set of options.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is a second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used both formally and informally in Brazilian Portuguese and formally in European Portuguese.</div><div><strong>prefere?</strong> This comes from the verb "preferir", which means "to prefer". The ending "e?" indicates that it is in the second-person singular present indicative form. It is a question, thus the question mark.</div><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>cinza</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "gray". It’s a masculine singular noun and here it refers to the color of an object.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction meaning "or". It is used to offer another option or alternative.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is repeated because in Portuguese, before each option in a choice, the definite article comes again. It remains "the" as the English equivalent.</div><div><strong>branco?</strong> Similar to "cinza", "branco" is a Portuguese noun meaning "white". It is also masculine singular, corresponding to "gray" in the sentence, and ends with a question mark, reinforcing that it is part of the question.</div>','<h2>Ele também tem muito talento.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the Portuguese third-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This is the Portuguese adverb for "also" or "too". It indicates that the subject has a certain quality in addition to others previously mentioned or understood.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It signifies possession, in this case, possessing talent.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "very" or "much". It is used here to amplify the noun that follows - it indicates a large amount or high degree of the quality.</div><div><strong>talento</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "talent". It’s a masculine noun that denotes skill or natural aptitude for something.</div>','<h2>Ela também corre no parque com frequência.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "also". It’s used here to indicate that the action of running is another activity that she does.</div><div><strong>corre</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "correr", which means "to run". It describes the action taken by the subject.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the). It translates to "in the" in English and is used here to refer to the location where the action occurs.</div><div><strong>parque</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "park". It’s the location where the action of running is taking place.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This Portuguese preposition translates to "with" in English.</div><div><strong>frequência</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "frequency". The phrase "com frequência" translates to "frequently" or "often" in English, describing the regularity of the action.</div>','<h2>Eu também te amo!</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This word means "also" or "too" in English. It is used here to express agreement or shared feeling with a previous statement.</div><div><strong>te</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when used as an object pronoun.</div><div><strong>amo</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "amar", which means "to love". It shows the action of loving directed towards the person referred to by "te".</div>','<h2>Ela também come frutas.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, referring to a female person.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This word translates to "also" in English. It is an adverb used to add a piece of information that is similar to what has previously been mentioned.</div><div><strong>come</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "comer", which means "to eat". It demonstrates the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>frutas</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "fruta" in Portuguese, meaning "fruits". It’s the object of the sentence, indicating what is being eaten by the subject.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Sim, eu toco violão e piano.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It is used to affirm a statement or respond affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>toco</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "tocar", which means "to play" an instrument in this context.</div><div><strong>violão</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "guitar". In Brazil, it specifically refers to an acoustic guitar. It is the object of the verb "tocar".</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words or phrases in a sentence.</div><div><strong>piano</strong> This is a noun in both Portuguese and English, and it denotes a type of musical instrument. Here, it’s used as a second object of the verb "tocar".</div>','<h2>Eu li um livro e dormi muito.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>li</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "ler", which means "to read". It indicates that the action was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" in English. It is used before masculine singular nouns.</div><div><strong>livro</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "book".</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>dormi</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "dormir", which means "to sleep". Similar to "li", it indicates that the action was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "a lot" or "much". Here, it’s used to indicate the extent or degree of how much the subject slept.</div>','<h2>Você pode aprender e se divertir!</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This comes from the verb "poder", which means "to be able to" or "can". It is in the third-person singular of the present indicative, used here with "Você".</div><div><strong>aprender</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to learn" in Portuguese. It is used here following "pode", indicating what "you" can do.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>se divertir</strong> This is a reflexive verb phrase, "divertir-se", meaning "to have fun" or "to enjoy oneself" in Portuguese. In this case, "se" refers back to the subject "Você", and "divertir" is in the infinitive form because it follows the conjunction "e".</div>','<h2>Adoramos dançar e cantar.</h2><div><strong>Adoramos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "adorar", which means "to love" or "to adore" in English. It conveys a strong liking or enjoyment of something by the subjects. In this case, it indicates that "we love".</div><div><strong>dançar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "dançar", which means "to dance" in English. It functions as the object of affection for the verb "adoramos", telling what we love to do.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses in a sentence.</div><div><strong>cantar</strong> Similar to "dançar", this is the infinitive form of the verb "cantar", which means "to sing" in English. It is the second activity that "we love" to do, connected to the first by the conjunction "e".</div>','<h2>Trabalho e depois descanso.</h2><div><strong>Trabalho</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work" in Portuguese. It indicates an action being performed by the speaker.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect verbs or clauses in a sentence.</div><div><strong>depois</strong> This is an adverb meaning "afterwards" or "then" in English. It indicates that the action of resting will occur after the action of working.</div><div><strong>descanso</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "descansar", which means "to rest" in Portuguese. It shows what the speaker will do after working.</div>','<h2>Tomei banho e logo me vesti.</h2><div><strong>Tomei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "tomar", which means "to take" in English. In this context, it is part of the expression "tomar banho", which means "to take a shower" or "to bathe".</div><div><strong>banho</strong> This is a noun meaning "bath" or "shower" in English. It is the object of the action described by the verb "tomar".</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "and" in English. It connects the actions of taking a shower and getting dressed.</div><div><strong>logo</strong> This adverb means "immediately" or "soon after" in English. It indicates that the action that follows happened right after taking a bath.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun meaning "myself" in English. It reflects the action of the verb back onto the subject, indicating that the subject performed the action on themselves.</div><div><strong>vesti</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "vestir", which means "to dress" in English. The reflexive form "vestir-se" means "to dress oneself".</div>','<h2>Ele entrou e me deu uma caixa grande.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>entrou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "entrar", which means "to enter". It indicates the action he performed.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, used as an indirect object pronoun equivalent to "to me" or "for me" in English.</div><div><strong>deu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "dar", which means "to give". It refers to the action performed by the subject towards the indirect object.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This word is an indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes a feminine singular noun.</div><div><strong>caixa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "box". It is feminine and singular to agree with the indefinite article "uma".</div><div><strong>grande</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective that means "large" or "big". It describes the noun "caixa" and agrees with it in gender and number (feminine singular).</div>','<h2>Nós temos água, suco de maçã, café e chá.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>temos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". This verb indicates possession or existence of something.</div><div><strong>água</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "water". It is a noun in its singular form.</div><div><strong>suco</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "juice". It is a noun in its singular form.</div><div><strong>de maçã</strong> This is a Portuguese prepositional phrase meaning "of apple". It specifies the type of juice. "de" is the preposition "of" and "maçã" is the singular form of "apple".</div><div><strong>café</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "coffee". It is a noun in its singular form and is a popular beverage.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect words or groups of words in a list.</div><div><strong>chá</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "tea". It is a noun in its singular form and refers to the beverage made by infusing dried leaves in hot water.</div>','<h2>Comi um ovo e depois comi outro.</h2><div><strong>Comi</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "comer", which means "to eat" in English. It indicates that the action has been completed.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, used here in the singular masculine form. It is equivalent to "a" in English.</div><div><strong>ovo</strong> This is a masculine noun in Portuguese, which means "egg" in English.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "and" in English. It is used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>depois</strong> This is an adverb of time in Portuguese, which means "after" or "later" in English.</div><div><strong>comi</strong> This is repeated from the first part of the sentence and again is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "comer", meaning "I ate".</div><div><strong>outro</strong> This is an adjective and pronoun in Portuguese, which means "another" or "other" in English. Here, it refers to "another one", implying "another egg".</div>','<h2>Gosto de ver você sorrir e se divertir.</h2><div><strong>Gosto</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" or "to enjoy" in Portuguese. It expresses a personal preference or pleasure.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition commonly translated into English as "of" or "from". In this sentence, "de" is part of the verbal phrase "gosto de", which together means "I like to".</div><div><strong>ver</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ver", which means "to see" or "to watch" in Portuguese. It functions as the direct object of the verb "gosto de", indicating what the speaker enjoys doing.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is a second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the object of the action described by the verb "ver", indicating whom the speaker likes to watch.</div><div><strong>sorrir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "sorrir", which means "to smile" and is another action that the speaker enjoys seeing you do.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word is a conjunction in Portuguese, equivalent to "and" in English. It’s used to connect the actions of smiling and having fun.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. In the context of this sentence, it is part of the reflexive verb "se divertir", which means "to enjoy oneself" or "to have fun".</div><div><strong>divertir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "divertir", which means "to amuse" or "to entertain". As part of the reflexive verb "se divertir", it means "to have fun".</div>','<h2>O seu cachorro é preto e o meu é branco.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which means "your" in English. It indicates possession and is agreeing in gender and number with the noun it refers to, which is "cachorro" (dog).</div><div><strong>cachorro</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "dog" in English.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It is used here to denote the state of being of the subject "cachorro".</div><div><strong>preto</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "black". It’s used here in its masculine singular form to agree with the noun "cachorro".</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>o</strong> Repeated use of the Portuguese definite article for masculine singular nouns, again translating to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This is another possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which means "my" in English. It indicates possession and also agrees in gender and number with the noun it refers to, which in this case is implied, "cachorro".</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is again the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser". It is used here for the second subject, which is the speaker’s own dog.</div><div><strong>branco</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "white". Similar to "preto", it agrees in gender and number with the noun it describes.</div>','<h2>Ela cheirou a sopa e gostou do aroma.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>cheirou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "cheirar", which means "to smell". It indicates that the action of smelling has been completed in the past.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to specify the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>sopa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "soup". It is the object of the verb "cheirar" here, indicating what she smelled.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>gostou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "gostar", which means "to like". It indicates that she experienced a feeling of pleasure or approval.</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is the contraction of the preposition "de" (of/from) and the definite article "o" (the), translating as "of the" or "from the" in English.</div><div><strong>aroma</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "aroma" or "scent". It is the object of the verb "gostar", indicating what she liked.</div>','<h2>Nós apagaremos tudo e começaremos de novo.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>apagaremos</strong> This is the future tense of the verb "apagar", which means "to erase" or "to delete" in English. In this sentence, it’s conjugated with "nós", indicating that the subject will perform the action in the future.</div><div><strong>tudo</strong> This means "everything" in Portuguese. It’s an indefinite pronoun used here to refer to all things that will be erased.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "and". It’s a conjunction used to connect two verbs in the sentence.</div><div><strong>começaremos</strong> This is the future tense of the verb "começar", which means "to begin" or "to start" in English. Similar to "apagaremos", it’s conjugated with "nós", implying that the subject will begin something in the future.</div><div><strong>de novo</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase that translates to "again" or "anew" in English. It indicates that the action of beginning will start from scratch or be repeated.</div>','<h2>Menti para o meu pai e não sei o que fazer.</h2><div><strong>Menti</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense of the verb "mentir", which means "to lie" in English. It indicates that the speaker deceived someone.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated as "to" or "for" in English. It indicates direction or the recipient of an action.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English, in its masculine singular form, used before masculine singular nouns in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>meu</strong> This word is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that means "my" in English. It denotes ownership or a relationship to the speaker.</div><div><strong>pai</strong> This is a noun that means "father" in English. It’s the person being lied to in this sentence.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word is a conjunction in Portuguese that translates to "and" in English. It’s used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the word for "not" in English. It negates a statement or part of a sentence.</div><div><strong>sei</strong> This is the first-person singular present form of the verb "saber", which means "to know" in English. It’s used here to express uncertainty or lack of knowledge about something.</div><div><strong>o que</strong> This phrase translates to "what" in English. It’s used to ask for information or clarification about something.</div><div><strong>fazer</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to do" or "to make" in English. It indicates an action that the speaker is uncertain about. </div>','<h2>Você tem irmãos ou irmãs?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Brazilian Portuguese pronoun for "you" in the second-person singular. It is used here as the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular of the present indicative tense of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. However, when conjugated with "você", it agrees with the second-person singular because "você" is grammatically treated like the third-person in Brazilian Portuguese.</div><div><strong>irmãos</strong> This is the masculine plural noun for "brothers" in Portuguese. It can refer to male siblings or a mix of male and female siblings when using the generic masculine.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "or". It’s a conjunction used to connect alternatives.</div><div><strong>irmãs?</strong> This is the feminine plural noun for "sisters" in Portuguese, referring only to female siblings. The question mark indicates that this is a question asking whether the person has siblings and specifies the gender of the siblings.</div>','<h2>Eu serei paga semanalmente ou mensalmente?</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>serei</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It indicates a future action or state.</div><div><strong>paga</strong> This is the feminine form of the past participle of the verb "pagar", which means "to pay" in Portuguese. In this context, it means "paid". The gender of this participle matches the speaker who is presumably female. If the speaker were male, it would be "pago".</div><div><strong>semanalmente</strong> This is an adverb of time in Portuguese, meaning "weekly". It indicates the frequency of the payment.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This word translates to "or" in English. It’s a conjunction used to offer alternatives or choices.</div><div><strong>mensalmente?</strong> This is another adverb of time in Portuguese, meaning "monthly". It also indicates the frequency of the payment and is the second option presented in the question.</div>','<h2>Esta é a sua opinião ou um fato?</h2><div><strong>Esta</strong> This is the feminine singular form of the demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "this". It’s used here to refer to something that was probably mentioned before in the conversation.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It links the subject with a complement, providing information about it.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, meaning "the". It’s used here in the feminine singular form to accompany the noun "opinião".</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "your". It shows ownership and is agreeable in gender and number with the noun it modifies, in this case, "opinião" (opinion).</div><div><strong>opinião</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "opinion". It’s a view or judgment formed about something, not necessarily based on fact or knowledge.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "or". It’s a conjunction used to connect alternatives, in this case between an "opinion" and a "fact".</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, meaning "a". It’s used here in the masculine singular form to accompany the noun "fato".</div><div><strong>fato</strong> This Portuguese noun means "fact". It’s a piece of information used as evidence or as part of a report or news article.</div>','<h2>Nós temos biscoito, pretzel ou amendoim.</h2><div><strong>Nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>temos</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have". It indicates possession or existence of something by the subject.</div><div><strong>biscoito</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "cookie" or "biscuit" in English. It indicates one of the snack options available.</div><div><strong>pretzel</strong> This is a loanword from German used in Portuguese, meaning "pretzel" in English as well. It indicates another snack option available.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "or". It’s a conjunction used to connect alternative options or choices.</div><div><strong>amendoim</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "peanut" in English. It indicates another choice of the snack options available.</div>','<h2>Tu preferes ir à direita ou à esquerda?</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and is used in informal contexts.</div><div><strong>preferes</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "preferir", which means "to prefer". It denotes preference or choice between options or actions.</div><div><strong>ir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "ir", which means "to go" in English. It’s used here to propose possible directions for movement.</div><div><strong>à</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition which here means "to" and is used in conjunction with directions. In this case, it is used twice: before "direita" and "esquerda".</div><div><strong>direita</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "right". It refers to the direction one might choose to go.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction meaning "or". It is used to offer a choice between two options.</div><div><strong>à esquerda?</strong> Similar to "à direita", the preposition "à" is used before "esquerda" which means "left" in English, to indicate the other choice of direction.</div>','<h2>Você prefere um assento no corredor ou na janela?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Portuguese second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here to address one person directly.</div><div><strong>prefere</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "preferir", which means "to prefer". In this context, it aligns with "você", functioning as a polite form to ask someone’s preference.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for masculine singular nouns, which translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>assento</strong> This is a masculine noun in Portuguese, meaning "seat".</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), which translates to "in the" when referring to masculine nouns. Here it indicates location.</div><div><strong>corredor</strong> This is a masculine noun which means "aisle" in English. Within this sentence, it refers to the aisle seat on a plane, a bus, or in a theater.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is a conjunction that means "or" in English. It’s used to offer a choice between two options.</div><div><strong>na</strong> Similarly to "no", this is a contraction of the preposition "em" and the definite article "a" (the), this time in the feminine form. It translates to "in the" when referring to feminine nouns and shows the location here.</div><div><strong>janela</strong> This is a feminine noun that means "window" in English. In this sentence, it refers to a window seat.</div>','<h2>Que bom. A senhora gostaria de um café ou chá?</h2><div><strong>Que</strong> This is the Portuguese word used to introduce a statement or an exclamation, equivalent to "what" or "that" in English, depending on the context. Here, it is part of the expression "Que bom", which means "How good" or "That’s good".</div><div><strong>bom</strong> This is the Portuguese adjective for "good". It agrees in gender and number with the noun it qualifies. In this sentence, it does not accompany a noun, but instead completes the expression "Que bom" used to express satisfaction or happiness.</div><div><strong>A senhora</strong> This phrase means "the lady" or "the woman" in Portuguese and is a formal, polite way to address a woman, equivalent to "ma’am" or "madam" in English.</div><div><strong>gostaria</strong> This is the third-person singular conditional tense of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" or "to enjoy". It can be translated to "would like" in this context, indicating a polite inquiry about someone’s preference.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that can have several meanings including "of", "from", or "about", depending on the context. Here, it is part of the phrase "gostaria de", which means "would like to have" when followed by a noun.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for the masculine singular noun, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>café</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "coffee". It’s a masculine noun and is commonly used when offering a beverage.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "or". It’s a conjunction used to connect alternatives.</div><div><strong>chá</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "tea". It’s a masculine noun and is another common beverage offered.</div>','<h2>Claro. O senhor quer gasolina comum ou premium?</h2><div><strong>Claro</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "clearly" or "of course". It is often used to affirm or agree with what has been said before.</div><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article "the" in Portuguese, masculine singular, used here before a masculine singular noun or title.</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "sir" or "mister". It is a formal way to address a man, equivalent to the English "Mr". or "sir".</div><div><strong>quer</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". It implies a query about someone’s desire or choice.</div><div><strong>gasolina</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "gasoline" or "petrol". It refers to the fuel used for engines.</div><div><strong>comum</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "regular" or "common". In the context of gasoline, it refers to the standard or normal grade of fuel.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "or". It is used as a conjunction to offer choices or alternatives.</div><div><strong>premium</strong> This is a loanword in Portuguese, taken from English, used to describe a higher quality or grade of product. In the context of gasoline, it refers to a higher octane fuel that is often more expensive but provides better performance or efficiency.</div>','<h2>Eu gostaria de fazer compras ou assistir a um filme.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gostaria</strong> This is the conditional tense of the verb "gostar", which means "to like", indicating a polite desire or wish equivalent to "would like" in English.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This preposition is used in Portuguese to mean "of" or "from", but is often used in conjunction with verbs to express intention or purpose, similar to "to" in English.</div><div><strong>fazer</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to do" or "to make" in Portuguese. Here, it’s used to indicate the action "to do shopping".</div><div><strong>compras</strong> This is the noun for "purchases" or "shopping". In the context of the sentence, "fazer compras" translates to the activity of "shopping".</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This conjunction in Portuguese means "or", and it is used to connect alternatives.</div><div><strong>assistir a</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to watch" in Portuguese, often followed by "a" when used with the direct object of what is being watched.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "a" in English.</div><div><strong>filme</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "movie" or "film".</div>','<h2>Você quer enviá-la pelo correio normal ou expresso?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>quer</strong> This is the third-person singular of the present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". It’s conjugated to match the subject "Você".</div><div><strong>enviá-la</strong> This is a combination of the verb "enviar", which means "to send", in its infinitive form, with the clitic pronoun "la", which means "her" or "it" in English, replacing a feminine singular noun. This structure indicates the object that is to be sent, and in this case, "la" refers to something previously mentioned in the conversation.</div><div><strong>pelo</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "por" (by, through) with the masculine singular definite article "o" to mean "through the" or "by the".</div><div><strong>correio</strong> This is a common Portuguese noun that means "mail" or "postal service".</div><div><strong>normal</strong> As an adjective, "normal" in Portuguese is the same as in English and means "standard" or "regular".</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This word translates to "or" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect alternative possibilities.</div><div><strong>expresso</strong> This is an adjective meaning "express" as in "express mail". It’s referring to a faster, usually more expensive, postal service.</div>','<h2>Você se lembra se o assaltante era um homem ou uma mulher?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the personal pronoun "you" in Portuguese, specifically used for the second-person singular subject in a formal or informal context in Brazil. In Portugal, it’s typically more formal. It’s used here to address the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This serves as a reflexive pronoun or a particle in certain verbal constructions in Portuguese. In this sentence, it is part of the reflexive verb structure "se lembra", which means "remember" in a reflexive form, akin to "remember (yourself)" i.e., "do you remember".</div><div><strong>lembra</strong> This verb comes from "lembrar", which means "to remember" in Portuguese. Here it is in the third-person singular present tense form, agreeing with the reflexive construction implied by "Você se".</div><div><strong>se</strong> This word is also used as a conjunction in Portuguese equivalent to "if" in English. It introduces the conditional clause that follows.</div><div><strong>o assaltante</strong> This is a noun phrase where "o" is the definite article "the" in masculine form and "assaltante" means "assailant" or "robber". Altogether, "o assaltante" refers to "the assailant".</div><div><strong>era</strong> This is the past imperfect tense of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It’s used in this sentence to describe a past condition or state of being.</div><div><strong>um homem</strong> This is a noun phrase where "um" is the indefinite article "a" in masculine form and "homem" means "man". Altogether, "um homem" refers to "a man".</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is the conjunction "or" in Portuguese, used to connect alternative possibilities.</div><div><strong>uma mulher?</strong> This is a noun phrase where "uma" is the indefinite article "a" in feminine form and "mulher" means "woman". Altogether, "uma mulher" refers to "a woman". The question mark indicates that this is part of a question.</div>','<h2>Você também pode ter náuseas.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "also" or "too". It indicates that the action of the verb can apply to the subject as well as to others previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "to be able to" or "can". It indicates possibility.</div><div><strong>ter</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese which means "to have". In this context, it’s paired with "pode" to express the possibility of experiencing something, which is "náuseas".</div><div><strong>náuseas</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "nausea". It is a feminine plural word that refers to the sensation of feeling sick with an inclination to vomit.</div>','<h2>Eu também estou aqui de férias.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It’s used here to express that the speaker is similarly engaging in the action or state mentioned by someone else.</div><div><strong>estou</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary state or location. It describes the speaker’s current state of being.</div><div><strong>aqui</strong> This Portuguese adverb means "here". It specifies the location where the speaker is.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can have many uses. In this sentence, it is part of the expression "de férias", which translates to "on vacation". It’s used to link the noun "férias" with the verb "estou".</div><div><strong>férias</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "vacation" or "holidays". It signifies the reason for the speaker’s presence in the location.</div>','<h2>Eu também quero um pouco de cuscuz.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "I". It is the subject pronoun used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This Portuguese word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It is used to express agreement or a similar action or desire.</div><div><strong>quero</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want" in Portuguese. It expresses the subject’s desire or intention.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a Portuguese indefinite article that translates to "a" or "an" in English. In this sentence, it is used before the noun to denote any amount or number.</div><div><strong>pouco</strong> This Portuguese word means "a little" or "some" in English, indicating a small quantity or amount.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is the Portuguese preposition for "of" indicating possession or characteristic.</div><div><strong>cuscuz</strong> This is a Portuguese term for "couscous", which is a type of North African dish made from steamed balls of crushed durum wheat semolina that is common also in Brazilian cuisine.</div>','<h2>Legal! Eu também quero ir para lá.</h2><div><strong>Legal!</strong> This is a colloquial Brazilian Portuguese interjection meaning "Cool!" or "Great!" It’s used to express approval or enthusiasm about something.</div><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It’s an adverb that indicates the speaker is adding to or agreeing with something previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>quero</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". It expresses the speaker’s desire or will.</div><div><strong>ir</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese that translates to "to go" in English. It’s used here with "quero" to express a wish or intention to go somewhere.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can mean "to" or "for" in English. It’s used here to indicate direction or destination.</div><div><strong>lá</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "there". It points to a location that is not close to the speaker or listener.</div>','<h2>Ele também construiu esse banheirinho.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "also" or "too". It indicates that the action of building was performed in addition to some other action or characteristic previously mentioned or understood.</div><div><strong>construiu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "construir", which means "to build". It indicates that the subject completed the action of building.</div><div><strong>esse</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese meaning "this". It indicates that the speaker is referring to a specific object close to the speaker or contextually obvious to both the speaker and listener.</div><div><strong>banheirinho</strong> This is a diminutive form of "banheiro", which means "bathroom" in Portuguese. The diminutive "-inho" suffix suggests the bathroom is small, implying affection or a diminutive size.</div>','<h2>Eu também gostaria de enviar esta carta.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This is the Portuguese adverb for "also" or "too". It indicates that the speaker is adding information in agreement or similarity to what was mentioned before.</div><div><strong>gostaria</strong> This is the first-person singular of the conditional tense of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" or "to want". In this form, it translates to "would like" in English, expressing a polite desire or wish.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is the Portuguese preposition for "of" or "from", but in this context, it is part of the verbal phrase "gostaria de" which sets up the following infinitive verb.</div><div><strong>enviar</strong> This is the Portuguese infinitive form of the verb "to send". It’s linked with "gostaria de" to express what the speaker would like to do.</div><div><strong>esta</strong> This is the feminine singular form of the demonstrative pronoun "this" in Portuguese. It specifies which letter the speaker is referring to.</div><div><strong>carta</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "letter". It’s a feminine noun, which is why it’s preceded by the feminine demonstrative pronoun "esta".</div>','<h2>Sim. Eu também gostaria de uma televisão.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It is an affirmative response to a question or agreement with a statement.</div><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This translates to "also" or "too" in English. It is used to express agreement or that the speaker shares a similar opinion or desire.</div><div><strong>gostaria</strong> This is the first-person singular conditional tense of the verb "gostar", which means "to like". In this context, "gostaria" translates to "would like", expressing a polite desire or interest.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition often translated to "of" or "from" in English, but can also be used in this context as part of the phrase "gostaria de" meaning "would like to have" or expressing a wish for something.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is the indefinite article "a" or "an" in English and it is gendered in Portuguese. It accompanies feminine singular nouns and here it precedes "televisão".</div><div><strong>televisão</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in Portuguese which means "television". When combined with the article "uma", it translates to "a television".</div>','<h2>Só uma, mas eu também tenho bagagem de mão.</h2><div><strong>Só</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "only" or "just". It indicates a limitation or a singular instance in this context.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is the Portuguese indefinite article for the feminine singular, meaning "one". In this sentence, it refers to one item, possibly in the context of a quantity, such as "just one" (ticket, suitcase, etc.).</div><div><strong>mas</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "but". It is a conjunction used to introduce a clause contrasting with what has been mentioned before.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English.</div><div><strong>também</strong> This translates to "also" or "too" in English. It’s used to add information to the sentence that is in addition to what has been previously stated.</div><div><strong>tenho</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>bagagem de mão</strong> This is a Portuguese noun phrase meaning "hand luggage" or "carry-on baggage". It refers to the type of luggage that passengers can take with them into the cabin of an airplane.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);